article.headline: Arkansas 77, Oral Roberts 71
article.story: FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansas pulled off a revenge 77-71 win against Oral Roberts Thursday, shaking off last season's disappointing early losses to non-conference opponents. Last season the Razorbacks dropped games to Oral Roberts, Illinois, Tulsa and Memphis to start Southeastern Conference play at 5-6 instead of 9-2 or 8-3 in Stan Heath's first season as coach. By scratching out the win against Oral Roberts (3-3) after trailing by as much as 10 in the first half, the Razorbacks are now 4-0 going into Saturday's game at No. 11 Illinois. "It's good to win a close one and play a good team to do it," said Arkansas sophomore guard Eric Ferguson, who tied Jonathan Modica with 18 points. Modica, another sophomore who was on the team last year, scored 14 of his points in the second half, and made a pair of key steals in the final two minutes. "I saw us able to handle some adversity," Heath said. "That was a good sign for us that we were able to hold on." The Razorbacks won despite shooting poorly at the free throw line, making just 14 of 30, and an interior defense that gave up 40 points in the paint. "The free throws have got to step up," Heath said. "We're not going to be able to do that." Oral Roberts (3-3) tied the game at 67-67 with a 3-pointer by Ken Tutt, who led the team with 17 points, with 2{ minutes left in the game. Billy Pharis, who had a career-high 12 points, gave Arkansas the lead and the back-to-back steals by Modica pushed the lead to 72-67 with a little over a minute remaining. Modica stole the ball from freshman Ken Tutt both times. "I was trying to get to the lane and make a play and put some points on the board," said Tutt, who led Oral Roberts with 17 points. "Modica came in and stripped the ball from me and took it down court. That was a costly play." Vincent Hunter blocked a 3-point attempt by Ralph Charles and Arkansas made 5 of 8 free throws to close out the win. "There were a lot of key defensive plays that maybe stopped the momentum swing," Heath said. Ronnie Brewer added 14 points, six rebounds and five assists, but he was one of the poorest shooters from the line, making just 1 of 7. "It feels good to win this close game," Modica said. "Last year we didn't like the way it turned out over there and we wanted to win this game a lot. This gives us some confidence going into this weekend when we play Illinois." Arkansas used a pair of 11-2 runs, one at the end of the first half to get back in the game and another to start the second half for a 43-37 lead, to overcome Oral Roberts' strong start. "I thought Oral Roberts was gritty and they really challenged us with their offense, the ability they had in their offense and to play inside and out," Heath said. The Razorbacks, who had never trailed in three victories, took their first lead at 36-35 with a layup by Modica early in the second half. Four Oral Roberts turnovers led to five Arkansas points in the second-half run. The Golden Eagles didn't wilt, coming back to take a 52-49 lead following layups by Schulyer Thomas and Tutt. Oral Roberts took advantage of Arkansas' poor interior defense all night. "I really thought this would be a game we could come into and win," Oral Roberts coach Scott Sutton said. "Arkansas is a lot like us in that they are so young. They are going to get better and better as the year goes on." Tutt led five players in double figures. Caleb Green had 15 points, while Charles and Thomas added 11. Eric Fowlkes had 10. Oral Roberts took a 35-32 lead going into halftime with a midcourt shot at the buzzer by Jonathan Bluitt, the sophomore's first basket in six first-half attempts.
